  {
    "speaker": "interviewee",
    "tag": "LORETTA KOZAK",
    "text": "Well, the only thing I'd like to say is that living with a Holocaust survivor is a little bit different than two American people living together. There are a lot of things that I had to learn way back about his insecurities, about fears, about attitudes that were very foreign to me. I didn't know from-- fear. I didn't know about being persecuted. But he brought all of that into my life. And I realized that he was persecuted just because he was a Jew. And all the fears came through slowly through the years. He would have terrible nightmares at night during his sleep. He would shiver. He would holler out. He would cry out. And that lasted many, many, many years. And whenever he got together with his family or friends and they'd talk about the Holocaust, he was extremely upset that particular night because it brought things to the surface. And he didn't want them to surface. He rarely talked about it to the family, to the children--",
