  {
    "speaker": "interviewee",
    "tag": "LORETTA KOZAK",
    "text": "But I think he has a lot of courage-- came to this country with nothing, nothing, beaten down, no confidence in himself, as all the other survivors did. And he made his mind up that he was going to start a new life in a new country. I met Morris when he was here for two years. And we were married a year after that. And he worked very hard. He worked night and day to, to become a good provider, to get back some of the things that were taken from him. And there were many times when he should have been home. But I think he just got lost in work because it helped. It helped him to forget. And, and he did make a success of himself. And we are very proud of him. But it's hard for him, to this day, to realize that his family actually loves him and cares for him. It's very hard for him to get this through his head. He knows we love him. But the-- he can't feel it totally. He really can't. And we all understand this. And we cope with it. And hopefully, in the future, future generations will understand a little bit about what these people went through but how they live the rest of their lives with this burden.",
